        <name>22.1.1.2 Evaluating determinants</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span lang="en" class="multilang"&gt;Compute the determinants of
\[
\mathrm{A}=\begin{bmatrix}{@a@}&amp;amp;{@a@}&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;{@b@}&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;{@b@}&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ \end{bmatrix}
\ \text{ and } \
\mathrm{B}=\begin{bmatrix}{@a@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@c@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@c@}&amp;amp;0\\ 0&amp;amp;{@c@}&amp;amp;{@a@}&amp;amp;{@b@}\\ \end{bmatrix} .
\]
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span lang="fi" hidden="" class="multilang"&gt;Laske matriisien
\[
\mathrm{A}=\begin{bmatrix}{@a@}&amp;amp;{@a@}&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;{@b@}&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;{@b@}&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ \end{bmatrix}
\ \text{ ja } \
\mathrm{B}=\begin{bmatrix}{@a@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@c@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@c@}&amp;amp;0\\ 0&amp;amp;{@c@}&amp;amp;{@a@}&amp;amp;{@b@}\\ \end{bmatrix}
\]
determinantit.&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;p&gt;\(\operatorname{det}(\mathrm{A})=\) [[input:SAns1]] [[validation:SAns1]]&lt;/p&gt;
[[feedback:detA]]
&lt;p&gt;\(\operatorname{det}(\mathrm{B})=\) [[input:SAns2]] [[validation:SAns2]]&lt;/p&gt;
[[feedback:detB]]</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;span lang="en" class="multilang"&gt;Determinants can be calculated for example by reducing the matrix to an upper triangle matrix or developing the determinant with respect to some row or column. Let's compute \(\det(\mathrm{A})\) by developing it with respect to the first row:
\begin{eqnarray}
\det(\mathrm{A})&amp;amp;=&amp;amp;{@a@}\left| \begin{matrix}{@b@} &amp;amp; {@a@} \\ {@b@} &amp;amp; {@c@} \\
\end{matrix}\right| -{@a@} \left| \begin{matrix}{@a@} &amp;amp; {@a@} \\ {@a@} &amp;amp; {@c@} \\ \end{matrix}\right| +({@c@}) \left| \begin{matrix}{@a@} &amp;amp; {@b@} \\ {@a@} &amp;amp; {@b@} \\ \end{matrix}\right| \nonumber \\
&amp;amp;=&amp;amp; {@a@}({@b@}\cdot ({@c@})-{@a@}\cdot {@b@})-{@a@}({@a@}\cdot ({@c@})-{@a@}^2)+({@c@})({@a@}\cdot {@b@}-{@a@}\cdot {@b@})\nonumber \\
&amp;amp;=&amp;amp; {@TAns1@}. \nonumber
\end{eqnarray}

The column of \(\mathrm{B}\) with the most zeros is the second column, so let's develop the determinant with respect to that:
\[
\det(\mathrm{B}) = ({@c@})\left| \begin{matrix} {@a@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@c@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;{@c@}&amp;amp;0\\ \end{matrix}\right| .
\]
Here the \(3\times 3\)-determinant reduces to a \(2\times 2\)-determinant when developed with respect to the second column:
\[
\det(\mathrm{B})=({@c@})\cdot (-({@c@}))\left| \begin{matrix} {@a@}&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@c@}&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ \end{matrix}\right| = -{@d@}^2({@a@}^2-({@c@})^2)={@TAns2@}.
\]&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span lang="fi" hidden="" class="multilang"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div style="font-weight:bold"&gt;Mallivastaus:&lt;/div&gt;
Determinantti voidaan laskea joko muuntamalla se yl&#228;kolmiomuotoon tai kehitt&#228;m&#228;ll&#228; sopivan rivin tai sarakkeen mukaan. Lasketaan \(\det(\mathrm{A})\) kehitt&#228;m&#228;ll&#228; 1. rivin mukaan:
\begin{eqnarray}
\det(\mathrm{A})&amp;amp;=&amp;amp;{@a@}\left| \begin{matrix}{@b@} &amp;amp; {@a@} \\ {@b@} &amp;amp; {@c@} \\
\end{matrix}\right| -{@a@} \left| \begin{matrix}{@a@} &amp;amp; {@a@} \\ {@a@} &amp;amp; {@c@} \\ \end{matrix}\right| +({@c@}) \left| \begin{matrix}{@a@} &amp;amp; {@b@} \\ {@a@} &amp;amp; {@b@} \\ \end{matrix}\right| \nonumber \\
&amp;amp;=&amp;amp; {@a@}({@b@}\cdot ({@c@})-{@a@}\cdot {@b@})-{@a@}({@a@}\cdot ({@c@})-{@a@}^2)+({@c@})({@a@}\cdot {@b@}-{@a@}\cdot {@b@})\nonumber \\
&amp;amp;=&amp;amp; {@TAns1@}. \nonumber
\end{eqnarray}

Matriisissa \(\mathrm{B}\) on paljon nollia, eniten niit&#228; on 2. sarakkeessa, joten kehitet&#228;&#228;n determinantti sen mukaan:
\[
\det(\mathrm{B}) = ({@c@})\left| \begin{matrix} {@a@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@c@}&amp;amp;0&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ {@a@}&amp;amp;{@c@}&amp;amp;0\\ \end{matrix}\right| .
\]
T&#228;ss&#228; \(3\times 3\)-determinantti kannattaa kehitt&#228;&#228; 2. sarakkeen mukaan, jolloin saadaan
\[
\det(\mathrm{B})=({@c@})\cdot (-({@c@}))\left| \begin{matrix} {@a@}&amp;amp;{@c@}\\ {@c@}&amp;amp;{@a@}\\ \end{matrix}\right| = -{@d@}^2({@a@}^2-({@c@})^2)={@TAns2@}.
\]&lt;/span&gt;</generalfeedback>
